snippet.textDisplay:
While science is vital, and while I do love Tyson, as a historian let me offer another angle. Historically, human beings act on what they perceive or believe, not on facts. For example, in India in 1857 a rumor began to spread that the rifle cartridges for the rifles used by Indian troops had been greased with beef or pork fat. To use these paper cartridges a solider was trained to tear off the top with his teeth and pour the contents into the muzzle of his rifle. Beef being anathema to Hindus, and Pork being Anathema to Muslims and many Hindus made this a huge problem. Evidence indicates that a relatively small number of these cartridges made it to India, but the actual number is irrelevant and some historians even argue none made it into Indian hands. In any case, the rumor made Indian troops wary that any cartridges could have caused them to violate their religious beliefs. This confusion helped spark already smoldering resentment of British rule and began what the British dubbed the Mutiny of 1857, a massive rebellion across much of India.

History, even recent history, is filled with events where people acted on what they thought was true, not what was scientifically provable. We may have the capacity to understand science (well, some of us) but as a species we also still often act based on emotions and feelings like fear, anger, and hatred. None of which is to say scientists should stop trying to educate, just as historians won't stop teaching why scientists will have a tough time getting through to some people.

snippet.textDisplay:
I detest this know-it-all ever since I read a comprehensive book on GMO, Genetically Modified Organisms, mostly about food, and then later heard Tyson speaking on the subject and getting things wrong that he had obviously spent no time researching himself.

That is not what Carl Sagan would have done, and it saddens me a lot that Tyson somehow thinks he has inherited Carl Sagan's earned position as the interpreter of science to the American people, having done nothing himself to earn it.

But, not only that, he can never shut up, and always has to ham it up and take the spotlight anywhere he is as the arbiter of truth. Science is not the same as truth. Science is the provisional best explanation we have to stuff that we can measure, and there is a lot more stuff we do not know about than that which we do.

snippet.textDisplay: Unfortunately, for the last 20+ years there has been a serious war on science here in the USA. Particularly on the politically conservative side, there has been a lot of contempt expressed toward "experts" in any field, coupled with a belief that gut feelings and anecdotal information is far superior. Look at the antivaxer movement, scientifically illiterate parents with no medical knowledge to speak of trusting celebrities over doctors and scientists. We've had numerous episodes of creationism being introduced in biology classes and even have huge pseudo-scientific museums dedicated to anti-science teachings. I'm sure the better educated segment of the population will follow scientific guidelines, but there are huge swaths buying junk like silver solution or believing those like Trump who assume their hunch is more valid than evidence. This is going to be exacerbated by the fact most people don't trust the government to give out accurate information. The CDC has lost public trust, many media outlets are no longer considered trustworthy. If you have a poor science background/limited education, and you don't trust that on authority to give you accurate information, you're going to fall for quack therapies and products, and you're not going to do what must be done to reduce your risk of catching and spreading disease.
